  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Cocoa Rehabilitation and Intensification Programme (CORIP)&#x2013; Phase II</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Following the successful implementation of phase one of the Cocoa Rehabilitation and Intensification Programme (CORIP I) by Solidaridad West Africa, the Embassy of the Kingdom of Netherlands has provided funding for phase two (CORIP II) of the programme. CORIP II is a four-year programme with the aim of scaling up the gains made under the first phase of the programme in Ghana and Cote d&#x2019;Ivoire, while implementing the first phase design and approach in Liberia and Sierra Leone based on lessons learnt from implementing CORIP I in Ghana. CORIP II started in November 2017 and will run until December 2021. The programme is being implemented through four interventions areas namely 1) Access to finance, 2) Policy, institutional strengthening &amp; capacity building, 3) Women &amp; youth inclusion, and 4) Resilient cocoa systems.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Smallholder cocoa farmers, service providers, women and youth</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The second phase of the programme seeks to speed and scale up within the cocoa supply chain, the creation of Small and Medium Enterprises (SMEs) to deliver market-based rehabilitation and intensification services to farmers. The overarching goal of the programme is centered on large-scale adoption of sustainable cocoa production using private capital. The key towards achieving this large-scale adoption is to facilitate the development of small and medium enterprises (SMEs) that provide on-farm and post-harvest management services to cocoa farmers in a manner that is profitable to investors and cocoa farmers.</narrative>
  </description>
